0]])\n\n=== March ===\n* [[March 11]] &ndash; [[Edmondo De Amicis]], Italian novelist (b. [[1846]])\n* [[March 12]] &ndash; [[Susan Marr Spalding]], American poet (b. [[1841]])\n* [[March 27]] &ndash; [[Charles N. Sims]], American Methodist preacher, third chancellor of [[Syracuse University]] (b. [[1835]])\n* [[March 29]] \n** [[Eliza Trask Hill]], American journalist and activist (b. [[1840]])\n** [[Esther Pugh]], American temperance reformer  (b. [[1834]])\n* [[March 30]] &ndash; [[Chester Gillette]], American murderer (executed) (b. [[1883]])\n\n=== April ===\n* [[April 20]] &ndash; [[Henry Chadwick (writer)|Henry Chadwick]], English-born American baseball writer (b. [[1824]])\n* [[April 22]]\n** [[Qasim Amin]], Egyptian writer (b. [[1863]])\n** [[Henry Campbell-Bannerman|Sir Henry Campbell-Bannerman]], [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (b. [[1836]])\n* [[April 26]] &ndash; [[Karl M\u00f6bius]], German ecologist (b. [[1825]])\n\n=== May ===\n* [[May 2]] &ndash; [[Prince Yamashina Kikumaro]], Japanese Prince (b. [[1873]])\n* [[May 17]] &ndash; [[Carl Koldewey]], German explorer (b. [[1837]])\n* [[May 23]] &ndash; [[Fran\u00e7ois Copp\u00e9e]], French poet, novelist (b. [[1842]])\n* [[May 24]] &ndash; [[Old Tom Morris]], Scottish golfer (b. [[1821]])\n* [[May 26]] &ndash; [[Mirza Ghulam Ahmad]], Sikh Empire-born founder of the [[Ahmadiyya]] movement in Islam (b. [[1835]])\n* [[May 29]] &ndash; [[Eliza Trask Hill]], American activist, journalist, philanthropist (b. [[1840]])\n\n=== June ===\n* [[June 2]] &ndash; [[Redvers Buller|Sir Redvers Buller]], British general, Victoria Cross recipient (b. [[1839]])\n* [[June 5]] &ndash; [[Jef Lambeaux]], Belgian sculptor (b. [[1852]])\n* [[June 13]] &ndash; [[Henry Lomb]], German-American optician, founder of [[Bausch & Lomb]] (b. [[1828]])\n* [[June 14]] &ndash; [[Frederick Stanley, 16th Earl of Derby]], Governor-General of Canada, founder of the Stanley Cup (b. [[1841]])\n* [[June 20]] &ndash; [[Federico Chueca]], Spanish composer (b. [[1846]])\n* [[June 21]] &ndash; [[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]], Russian composer (b. [[1844]])\n* [[June 24]] &ndash; [[Grover Cleveland]], 22nd and 24th [[President of the United States]] (b. [[1837]])\n\n=== July ===\n[[File:Demetrius Vikelas.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Demetrius Vikelas]]]]\n[[File:Portrait of Antoine-Henri Becquerel.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Henri Becquerel]]]]\n[[File:Jan Berther.JPG|thumb|110px|Servant of God [[John Berthier]]]]\n[[File:Tomas estrada palma.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Tomas Estrada Palma]]]]\n[[File:Emperor Guangxu.jpg|thumb|110px|Emperor [[Guangxu]] of [[Qing dynasty|China]]]]\n* [[July 3]] &ndash; [[Joel Chandler Harris]], American author (b. [[1848]])\n* [[July 5]] &ndash; [[Jonas Lie (writer)|Jonas Lie]], Norwegian writer (b. [[1833]])\n* [[July 6]] &ndash; [[Felipe Calder\u00f3n y Roca]], Filipino politician (b. [[1868]])\n* [[July 19]] &ndash; [[Ignacio de Veintemilla]], 11th [[President of Ecuador]] (b. [[1828]])\n* [[July 20]] &ndash; [[Demetrius Vikelas]], 1st [[President of the International Olympic Committee]] (b. [[1835]])\n* [[July 22]] &ndash; [[Randal Cremer|Sir Randal Cremer]], English politician and pacifist, Nobel Prize laureate (b. [[1828]])\n* [[July 29]] &ndash; [[Estelle M. H. Merrill]], American journalist and editor (b. [[1858]])\n\n=== August ===\n* [[August 4]] &ndash; [[Radoje Domanovi\u0107]], Serbian writer (b. [[1873]])\n* [[August 7]] &ndash; [[Antonio Starabba, Marchese di Rudin\u00ec]], 12th [[Prime Minister of Italy]] (b. [[1839]])\n* [[August 10]] &ndash; [[Louise Chandler Moulton]], American author and critic (b. [[1835]])\n* [[August 24]] &ndash; [[\u00c9leuth\u00e8re Mascart]], French physicist (b. [[1837]])\n* [[August 25]] &ndash; [[Henri Becquerel]], French physicist, Nobel Prize laureate (b. [[1852]])\n* [[August 26]] &ndash; [[Tony Pastor]], American theater impresario (b. [[1837]])\n* [[August 31]] &ndash; [[Leslie Green]], British architect (b. [[1875]])\n\n=== September ===\n* [[September 17]] &ndash; [[Thomas Selfridge]], United States Army officer, first person killed in an airplane crash (b. [[1882]])\n* [[September 20]] &ndash; [[Pablo de Sarasate]], Spanish violinist, composer (b. [[1844]])\n* [[September 21]]\n** [[Arnold Burrowes Kemball|Sir Arnold Kemball]], British army officer and diplomat (b. [[1820]])\n** [[Nicol\u00e1s Salmer\u00f3n]], 3rd [[President of Spain]] (b. [[1838]])\n* [[September 25]] &ndash; [[Frank Robison]], American baseball executive, early owner of the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] (b. [[1852]])\n* [[September 29]] &ndash; [[Machado de Assis]], Brazilian author (b. [[1839]])\n\n=== October ===\n* [[October 11]] &ndash; [[Rita Cetina Guti\u00e9rrez]], Mexican educator, poet and activist (b. [[1846]])\n* [[October 16]] &ndash; [[John Berthier]], French [[Roman Catholic]] priest, missionary and servant of God (b. [[1840]])\n* [[October 18]] &ndash; [[Nozu Michitsura]], Japanese general (b. [[1840]])\n* [[October 26]] &ndash; [[Enomoto Takeaki]], Japanese ''samurai'', admiral (b. [[1836]])\n* [[October 30]] &ndash; [[Caroline Schermerhorn Astor]], American socialite (b. [[1830]])\n\n=== November ===\n* [[November 1]] &ndash; [[Julia Abigail Fletcher Carney]], American writer of poems, many of which were set to music (b. [[1823]])\n* [[November 3]] &ndash; [[Harro Magnussen]], German sculptor (b. [[1861]])\n* [[November 4]]\n** [[Richard Gerstl]], Austrian artist (b. [[1883]])\n** [[Tom\u00e1s Estrada Palma]], 1st [[President of Cuba]] (b. [[1832]])\n* [[November 7]]\n** [[Butch Cassidy]], American outlaw (b. [[1866]])\n** [[Sundance Kid]], American outlaw (b. [[1867]])\n* [[November 8]] \n** [[Josephine E. Keating]], American literary critic and musician (b. [[1838]])\n** [[Victorien Sardou]], French dramatist (b. [[1831]])\n* [[November 14]] &ndash; Emperor [[Guangxu]] of China (b. [[1871]])\n* [[November 15]] &ndash; [[Empress Dowager Cixi]] of China (b. [[1835]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Cixi {{!}} Biography & Facts |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Cixi |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |accessdate=8 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[November 17]] &ndash; [[Lydia Thompson]], English dancer, actress (b. [[1838]])\n* [[November 22]] &ndash; [[Paul Taffanel]], French flautist, composer (b. [[1844]])\n\n=== December ===\n* [[December 5]] &ndash; [[Mary H. Graves]], American minister, literary editor, writer (b. [[1839]])\n* [[December 13]] &ndash; [[Augustus Le Plongeon]], American archaeologist (b. [[1825]])\n\n=== Date unknown ===\n* [[Jacob W. Davis]], Latvian American tailor, inventor of jeans (b. [[1831]])\n* [[Eleanor Kirk]], American publisher (b. [[1831]])\n\n== Nobel Prizes ==\n[[File:Nobel medal.png|right|100px]]\n* [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Physics]] &ndash; [[Gabriel Lippmann]]\n* [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Chemistry]] &ndash; [[Ernest Rutherford]]\n* [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Medicine]] &ndash; [[\u00c9lie Metchnikoff]], [[Paul Ehrlich]]\n* [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Literature]] &ndash; [[Rudolf Christoph Eucken]]\n* [[Nobel Peace Prize|Peace]] &ndash; [[Klas Pontus Arnoldson]], [[Fredrik Bajer]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''The Annual Register for 1908'', British and world events [https://books.google.com/books?id=Vq8oAAAAYAAJ online]\n* Gilbert, Martin. ''A History of the Twentieth Century: Volume 1 1900-1933'' (1997); global coverage of politics, diplomacy and warfare; pp 105 \u2013 22.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1908}}\n[[Category:1908| ]]\n[[Category:Leap years in the Gregorian calendar]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Year dab|1908}}\n{{Year nav|1908}}\n{{C20 year in topic}}\n{{Year article header|1908}}\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\nAccording to [[NASA]] reports, 1908 was the coldest recorded year since [[1880]].<ref>[http://data.giss.nasa.gov/gistemp/ NASA - GISS Surface Temperature Analysis (GISTEMP)]</ref>\n[[Image:Babynew.jpg|thumb|left| 1908 [[Baby New Year]] on the cover of ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]''.]]\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January ===\n[[File:WikiProject Scouting fleur-de-lis dark.svg|thumb|120px|January 24: [[Scouting|Boy Scout]] movement.]]\n* [[January 1]] &ndash; The British [[Nimrod Expedition|''Nimrod'' Expedition]] led by [[Ernest Shackleton]] sets sail from New Zealand on the ''[[Nimrod (ship)|Nimrod]]'' for Antarctica.\n* [[January 3]] &ndash; A [[Solar eclipse of January 3, 1908|total solar eclipse]] is visible in Pacific Ocean, and is the 46th solar eclipse of [[Solar Saros 130]].\n* [[January 12]] &ndash; A long-distance [[history of radio|radio message]] is sent from the [[Eiffel Tower]] for the first time.\n* [[January 13]] &ndash; The [[Rhoads Opera House fire]] in [[Boyertown, Pennsylvania]] kills 170.\n* [[January 15]] &ndash; [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] Sorority is founded on the campus of Howard University, in Washington, D.C.\n* [[January 21]] &ndash; New York City passes the [[Sullivan Ordinance]], making it illegal for womento smoke in public, only to have the measure vetoed by the mayor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1908/01/21/archives/no-public-smoking-by-women-now-the-sullivan-ordinance-to-be-passed.html|title=No Public Smoking By Women Now|date=1908-01-21|work=The New York Times|page=1|accessdate=2018-01-27}}</ref>\n* [[January 24]] &ndash; [[Robert Baden-Powell]]'s ''[[Scouting for Boys]]'' begins publication in London. The book will sell over 100 million copies over time, and effectively begin the worldwide [[Scouting|Boy Scout]] movement.\n\n=== February ===\n* [[February 1]] &ndash; [[Lisbon Regicide]]: King [[Carlos I of Portugal]] and [[Lu\u00eds Filipe, Prince Royal of Portugal|Infante Luis Filipe]] are shot dead in [[Lisbon]]. \n* [[February 3]] &ndash; [[Panathinaikos A.O.|Panathinaikos]], a well known professional multi-sports club of [[Greece]], is founded in [[Athens]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=el&u=http://www.pao.gr/history/events%3Fid%3D156&prev=search|title=The Founding of Panathinaikos|last=|first=|date=|website=Panathinaikos|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n* [[February 12]] &ndash; The first around-the-world car race, the [[1908 New York to Paris Race]], begins.\n* [[February 18]] &ndash; [[Japanese Americans|Japanese emigration to the United States]] is forbidden, under terms of the [[Gentlemen's Agreement of 1907]].\n\n=== March ===\n* [[March]] &ndash; ''[[The Children's Encyclop\u00e6dia]]'' begins publication in London.\n* [[March 4]]\n** The [[Pretoria]] branch of the [[Transvaal University College]], precursor to the [[University of Pretoria]], is established.\n** The [[Collinwood school fire]] near [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]] kills 174.\n* [[March 9]] &ndash; [[Inter Milan]], a well-known football club in [[Italy]], is founded.<ref>{{cite web|title=Qualcosa di speciale? La Patch 105|url=http://www.inter.it/it/news/61746|work=Qualcosa di speciale?|accessdate=2013-10-03}}</ref>\n* [[March 23]] &ndash; American diplomat [[Durham Stevens]], an employee of Japan's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]], is assassinated in [[San Francisco]] by two [[Korean Americans|Korean immigrant]]s, unhappy with his recent support for the increasing Japanese presence in Korea.\n* [[March 27]] &ndash; The first [[Scouting|Scout troop]] outside the U.K. is formed in [[Gibraltar]].\n* [[March 29]] &ndash; French aviator [[Henri Farman]] made the world's first flight with a passenger, [[L\u00e9on Delagrange]].\n\n=== April ===\n* [[April 8]] &ndash; [[H. H. Asquith]] of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] takes office as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], succeeding Sir [[Henry Campbell-Bannerman]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=Roy|authorlink=Roy Jenkins|title=Asquith|edition=Third|year=1986|publisher=Collins|location=London|isbn=0002177129|pages=179\u2013180|chapter=An Assured Succession 1908}}</ref>\n* [[April 20]] &ndash; [[Sunshine rail disaster]]: A rear-end collision of two trains in [[Melbourne]], Australia kills 44 people, and injures more than 400.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ballaratgenealogy.org.au/goroke/wwm1908.htm |title=''Ballarat Genealogy'': Newspaper Report of the accident |publisher=ballaratgenealogy.org.au |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211154316/http://www.ballaratgenealogy.org.au/goroke/wwm1908.htm |archivedate=February 11, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[April 21]] &ndash; [[Frederick Cook]] claims to have reached the [[North Pole]] on this date.\n\n=== May ===\n* [[May 14]]&ndash;[[October 31]] &ndash; The [[Franco-British Exhibition (1908)]] is held in London.\n* [[May 26]] &ndash; At [[Masjed Soleyman]] in southwest [[Iran|Persia]], the first major commercial oil discovery in the Middle East is made. The rights to the resource are quickly acquired by the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n=== June ===\n[[File:Tunguska event fallen trees.jpg|thumb|240px|Evidence of the [[Tunguska event]] (June 30). Photo taken [[1927|19 years later.]]]]\n* [[June 28]] &ndash; An [[Solar eclipse of June 28, 1908|annular solar eclipse]] was visible from Central America, North America, Atlantic Ocean and Africa, and was the 33rd solar eclipse of [[Solar Saros 135]].\n* [[June 30]] (June 17 [[Old Style and New Style dates|OS]]) &ndash; The [[Tunguska event]] or \"Russian explosion\" near the [[Podkamennaya Tunguska River]] in [[Krasnoyarsk Krai]], [[Siberia]], [[Russian Empire]], is believed to have been caused by the [[air burst]] of a large [[meteoroid]] or [[comet]] fragment, at an altitude of {{convert|5|\u2013|10|km|0}} above the [[Earth]]'s surface.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pasechnik|first=I. P.|chapter=Refinement of the moment of explosion of the Tunguska meteorite from the seismic data|title=Cosmic Matter and the Earth|location=Novosibirsk|publisher=Nauka|year=1986|page=66|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Farinella |first=Paolo |last2=Foschini |first2=L. |last3=Froeschl\u00e9 |first3=Christiane |last4=Gonczi |first4=R. |last5=Jopek |first5=T. J. |last6=Longo |first6=G. |last7=Michel |first7=Patrick |url=http://www-th.bo.infn.it/tunguska/aah2886.pdf|title=Probable asteroidal origin of the Tunguska Cosmic Body|journal=[[Astronomy and Astrophysics|Astronomy & Astrophysics]]|volume=377|pages=1081\u20131097|year=2001|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20011054|accessdate=2011-08-23|bibcode=2001A&A...377.1081F}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Trayner|first=Chris|url=http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu//full/1994Obs...114..227T/0000227.000.html|title=Perplexities of the Tunguska Meteorite|journal=[[The Observatory (journal)|The Observatory]]|volume=114|pages=227\u2013231|year=1994|accessdate=2011-08-23|bibcode = 1994Obs...114..227T }}</ref>\n\n=== July ===\n[[File:Olympic games 1908 London.jpg|240px|thumbnail|right|[[1908 Summer Olympics]]]]\n* [[July 3]] &ndash; [[Young Turk Revolution]] in the [[Ottoman Empire]]: Major Ahmed Niyazi, with 200 followers (Ottoman troops and civilians), begins an open revolution by defecting from the 3rd Army Corps in [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]], decamping into the hill country.\n* [[July 6]] &ndash; [[Robert Peary]] sets sail for the [[North Pole]].\n* [[July 8]] &ndash; French aviator [[L\u00e9on Delagrange]] made the world's first flight with a female passenger, his partner and fellow sculptor [[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Peltier]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Therese Peltier|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/explore-and-learn/topics/women-in-aviation/Peltier.cfm|work=Women in aviation and space history|accessdate=2017-05-07}}</ref>\n* [[July 11]]&ndash;[[July 12|12]] &ndash; The steamship ''Amalthea'', housing 80 British [[strikebreaker]]s in [[Malm\u00f6]] harbour, [[Sweden]], is bombed by [[Anton Nilson]]; 1 is killed, 20 injured.\n* [[July 13]]&ndash;[[July 25|25]] &ndash; The [[1908 Summer Olympics]] are held in London (the Winter Olympics are held here from [[October 19]]&ndash;[[October 31|31]].<ref name=\"Pocket On This Day\">{{cite book|title=Penguin Pocket On This Day|publisher=Penguin Reference Library|isbn=0-14-102715-0|year=2006}}</ref>\n* [[July 23]] &ndash; [[Young Turk Revolution]]: The [[Committee of Union and Progress]] (CUP) issues a formal ultimatum to [[Abdul Hamid II|Sultan Abdul Hamid II]], to restore the constitution of [[1876]] within the [[Ottoman Empire]] (it is restored the following day).\n* [[July 24]] &ndash; Italian [[Dorando Pietri]] wins the Olympic [[marathon]] (run from [[Windsor Castle]] to London) in one of the most dramatic arrivals in Olympic history, only to be disqualified soon afterwards for receiving assistance; victory is awarded to Irish-American [[Johnny Hayes]].\n* [[July 27]]&ndash;[[July 28|28]] &ndash; The [[1908 Hong Kong typhoon]] sinks the passenger steamer ''Ying King'', causing 421 deaths.\n\n=== August ===\n* [[August 8]] \n** [[Wilbur Wright]] flies in France for the first time, demonstrating true controlled powered flight in Europe.\n** [[The Hoover Company]] of [[Canton, Ohio]], acquires manufacturing rights to the upright portable [[vacuum cleaner]] just invented by [[James M. Spangler]].\n* [[August 17]] &ndash; [[\u00c9mile Cohl]] makes the first fully [[animated film]], ''[[Fantasmagorie (1908 film)|Fantasmagorie]]''.\n* [[August 24]] &ndash; After an intense power struggle, Sultan [[Abdelaziz of Morocco]] is deposed, and is succeeded by his brother [[Abd al-Hafid of Morocco|Abd al-Hafid]].\n* [[August 31]] &ndash; The Great Storm of 1908 starts to pound the Bristol Channel, lasting into the morning of September 2.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/wales/entries/5ad4c6e6-91ff-3c7f-b663-fc3b5bc913b7</ref>\n\n=== September ===\n* [[September 10]] &ndash; The first [[Minas Geraes-class battleship|''Minas Geraes''-class]] [[Dreadnought]] [[battleship]] for [[Brazil]], ''[[Brazilian battleship Minas Geraes|Minas Geraes]]'' is launched at [[Armstrong Whitworth]]'s yard on the [[River Tyne]] in England, catalysing the \"[[South American dreadnought race]]\".\n* [[September 17]] &ndash; At [[Fort Myer]], [[Virginia]], [[Thomas Selfridge]] becomes the first person to die in an airplane crash. The pilot, [[Orville Wright]], is severely injured in the crash but recovers.\n* [[September 27]] &ndash; [[Henry Ford]] produces his first [[Ford Model T|Model T]] automobile at the [[Ford Piquette Avenue Plant]], in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]].\n\n=== October ===\n* [[October 1]] &ndash; [[Penny Post]] is established between the [[United Kingdom]] and [[United States]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Richard|last=Blake|title=The Book of Postal Dates, 1635-1985|location=Caterham|publisher=Marden|page=20}}</ref>\n* [[October 5]] &ndash; [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]] declares its independence from the [[Ottoman Empire]]; [[Ferdinand I of Bulgaria]] becomes [[Tsar]].\n* [[October 5]] &ndash; ''[[The Melting Pot (play)|The Melting Pot]]'', a play by [[Israel Zangwill]], opens in Washington, D.C.  The title quickly becomes a widely used symbol for assimilation of immigrants to the United States.\n* [[October 6]] &ndash; The [[Bosnian crisis]] begins, after the [[Austro-Hungarian Empire]] annexes [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]].\n* [[October 29]] &ndash; [[Olivetti]], the well known [[Typewriter|typewriter]] and business equipments company, is founded in [[Italy]].{{page needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n=== November ===\n* [[November 3]] &ndash; [[1908 United States presidential election]]: Republican candidate [[William Howard Taft]] defeats [[William Jennings Bryan]], 321 electoral votes to 162.\n* [[November 6]] &ndash; Western bandits [[Butch Cassidy]] and the [[Sundance Kid]] are supposedly killed in [[Bolivia]], after being surrounded by a large group of soldiers. There are many rumors to the contrary however, and their grave sites are unmarked.\n* [[November 15]] &ndash; King [[Leopold II of Belgium]] formally relinquishes his personal control of the [[Congo Free State]] (becoming [[Belgian Congo]]) to Belgium, following evidence collected by [[Roger Casement]] of maladministration.\n* [[November 25]]\n** ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'' newspaper is first published, in the United States.\n** A fire breaks out on {{SS|Sardinia|1888|6}} as it leaves Malta's [[Grand Harbour]], resulting in the ship's grounding and the deaths of at least 118 people.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gulf of Corcovado |url=http://www.tynebuiltships.co.uk/G-Ships/gulfofcorcovado1888.html |website=Tyne Built Ships |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708121648/http://www.tynebuiltships.co.uk/G-Ships/gulfofcorcovado1888.html |archivedate=8 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[November 28]] &ndash; A mine explosion in [[Marianna, Pennsylvania]], kills 154 men, leaving only one survivor.\n\n=== December ===\n* [[December 2]] &ndash; Young [[Emperor of China|Emperor]] [[Puyi]] ascends the Chinese throne at age 2.\n* [[December 16]] &ndash; Construction begins on the {{RMS|Olympic}}, at the [[Harland and Wolff]] Shipyard in [[Belfast]].\n* [[December 23]] &ndash; A [[Solar eclipse of December 23, 1908|hybrid solar eclipse]] is visible from Atlantic Ocean, and is the 23rd solar eclipse of [[Solar Saros 140]].\n* [[December 28]] &ndash; The 7.1 {{M|w}} [[1908 Messina earthquake|Messina earthquake]] shakes [[Southern Italy]] with a maximum [[Mercalli intensity scale|Mercalli intensity]] of XI (''Extreme''), killing between 75,000 and 200,000.\n\n=== Date unknown ===\n* A 40,000-year-old [[Neanderthal]] boy skeleton is found at [[Le Moustier]] in southwest France, by [[Otto Hauser]].\n* The Western University of Pennsylvania is renamed the [[University of Pittsburgh]].\n* The State Normal and Industrial School for Women, precursor to [[James Madison University]], is founded in [[Harrisonburg, Virginia]].\n* The University of Omaha, precursor of the [[University of Nebraska Omaha]] is founded as a private non-sectarian college.\n* [[Benjamin Franklin Institute of Technology]] in [[Boston]], Massachusetts, is established under the terms of Franklin's will.\n* [[Hitachi]], an [[electromechanics]] company, is founded as a mining machine repair factory in [[Ibaraki Prefecture]], [[Japan]].<ref>[[:ja:\u65e5\u7acb\u88fd\u4f5c\u6240#\u6b74\u53f2\u266f\u6cbf\u9769|\u65e5\u7acb\u88fd\u4f5c\u6240#\u6b74\u53f2\u266f\u6cbf\u9769]] Japanese language edition. Retrieved 2018-12-16.{{Better source|date=March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Births ==\n{{BDToC|births}}\n\n=== January ===\n[[File:Simone de Beauvoir2.png|thumb|100px|[[Simone de Beauvoir]]]]\n[[File:StephaneGrappelli25.JPG|thumb|100px|[[St\u00e9phane Grappelli]]]]\n* [[January 8]] &ndash; [[William Hartnell]], British actor (d. [[1975]])\n* [[January 8]] &ndash;  [[Fearless Nadia]] (Mary Evans), Indian Actress (d.[[1996]])\n* [[January 9]] &ndash; [[Simone de Beauvoir]], French feminist writer (d. [[1986]])\n* [[January 10]] &ndash; [[Paul Henreid]], Austrian-born American actor (d. [[1992]])\n* [[January 11]] &ndash; [[Lionel Stander]], American actor (d. [[1994]])\n* [[January 12]] &ndash; [[Jean Delannoy]], French film director (d. [[2008]])\n* [[January 14]] &ndash; [[Russ Columbo]], Italian-American singer, bandleader, and composer (d. [[1934]])\n* [[January 15]] &ndash; [[Edward Teller]], Hungarian-born physicist (d. [[2003]])\n* [[January 16]] &ndash; [[G\u00fcnther Prien]], German submarine commander (d. [[1941]])\n* [[January 17]] &ndash; [[Cus D'Amato]], American boxing trainer (d. [[1985]])\n* [[January 22]] &ndash; [[Lev Landau]], Russian physicist, Nobel Prize laureate (d. [[1968]])\n* [[January 24]] &ndash; [[Duncan Sandys]], British politician (d. [[1987]])\n* [[January 26]]\n** [[Rupprecht Geiger]], German painter (d. [[2009]])\n** [[St\u00e9phane Grappelli]], French jazz violinist, composer (d. [[1997]])\n* [[January 27]] &ndash; [[Hot Lips Page]], American jazz singer, trumpeter, and bandleader (d. [[1954]])\n\n=== February ===\n[[File:Amintore Fanfani 1983-04-14.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Amintore Fanfani]]]]\n[[File:RB 1975.jpg|100px|thumb|[[R\u00f3mulo Betancourt]]]]\n[[File:William McMahon 1966.jpg|thumb|100px|[[William McMahon]]]]\n* [[February 1]] &ndash; [[George Pal]], Hungarian-born American animator (d. [[1980]])\n* [[February 5]]\n**[[Peg Entwistle]], English actress (d. [[1932]])\n** [[Eugen Weidmann]], German serial killer, last person publicly executed in France (d. [[1939]])\n* [[February 6]]\n** [[Amintore Fanfani]], 32nd Prime Minister of Italy (d. [[1999]])\n** [[Michael Maltese]], American screenwriter (d. [[1981]])\n* [[February 7]] &ndash; [[Buster Crabbe]], American swimmer, actor (d. [[1983]])\n* [[February 11]] \n** [[Philip Dunne (writer)|Philip Dunne]], American screenwriter, director, and producer (d. [[1992]])\n** [[Vivian Fuchs]], English geologist, explorer (d. [[1999]])\n* [[February 12]] &ndash; [[Jean Effel]], French painter, journalist (d. [[1982]])\n* [[February 17]] &ndash; [[Bo Yibo]], Chinese politician (d. [[2007]])\n* [[February 19]] &ndash; [[Qin Hanzhang]], Chinese engineer (d. [[2019]])\n* [[February 22]]\n** [[R\u00f3mulo Betancourt]], [[President of Venezuela]] (d. [[1981]])\n** [[John Mills]], British actor (d. [[2005]])\n* [[February 23]] &ndash; [[William McMahon]], 20th Prime Minister of Australia (d. [[1988]])\n* [[February 25]] &ndash; [[George Duning]], American film composer (d. [[2000]])\n* [[February 26]]\n** [[Tex Avery]], American cartoonist (d. [[1980]])\n** [[Nestor Mesta Chayres]], Mexican operatic tenor and bolero vocalist (d. [[1971]])\n** [[Jean-Pierre Wimille]], French race car driver (d. [[1949]])\n* [[February 29]]\n** [[Balthus]], French painter (d. [[2001]])\n** [[Dee Brown (writer)|Dee Brown]], American writer, historian (d. [[2002]])\n\n=== March ===\n[[File:Olympia-Kanone 1936.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Walter Bruch]] behind camera]]\n[[File:Rex Harrison Allan Warren.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Rex Harrison]]]]\n[[File:Sir Michael Redgrave portrait.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Michael Redgrave]]]]\n[[File:DavidLean1965.jpg|thumb|100px|[[David Lean]]]]\n* [[March 2]] &ndash; [[Walter Bruch]], German engin